equation_narrative.headline: Hydrophobic core context drives confident leucine prediction from buried structural contacts
equation_narrative.story: Position 69 sits in a hydrophobic environment with 8 structural contacts, predominantly aliphatic. Early layers (1-17) show unstable logit-lens projections cycling through charged and polar residues (S, H, E, D, R) as the model reads local sequence context. By layer 13, the representation stabilizes toward hydrophobic character as structural contacts are integrated. The L/V competition dominates layers 17-23, reflecting the model's assembly of a buried aliphatic context. Decision phase (L24-33) sees leucine-specific prediction channels activate strongly, with MLP neurons N28:5086 and N32:3054 providing decisive votes that push L from 43% to 97%.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-17 show chaotic logit-lens behavior as the model processes local sequence (ESTLH[?]VLRLR), with charged residues (S, H, E, D, R) transiently leading—this reflects sequential reading of nearby charged positions, not predictions. Layer 9 attention features (F9:5728, F9:1281) encode positional and secondary structure context. Structural contact integration begins around L13-17, where attention heads read 8 nearby positions. The representation shifts decisively toward hydrophobic character at L13-17 (L rises from 3.9% to 14.9%), as buried aliphatic contacts dominate. By L23, the representation is strongly hydrophobic-leaning (L 42.9%, V 20.1%), consistent with a buried core position surrounded by leucine, valine, and arginine residues.
perception_phase.context_character: Buried hydrophobic core environment. Eight structural contacts provide aliphatic chemistry (neighboring L, V, R positions). Minimal co-evolutionary signal (3 positions) suggests local structural constraint rather than functional coupling. The representation by L23 encodes a position requiring a medium-to-large hydrophobic residue.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 8 residues read via attention heads, predominantly hydrophobic local environment (V70, L67, R72 in immediate vicinity)
L16-17 attention: head L16:12 writes +1.75 proj from local context, stabilizing hydrophobic representation
L18 features: F18:7701 and F18:9820 (13.0 proj each) encode buried position character with hydrophobic preference
Co-evolutionary signal: 3 coupled positions provide weak constraint, insufficient to override local structural chemistry

decision_phase.summary: Leucine-specific prediction channels activate at L24-26, with F24:5827 (23.6 proj) marking the transition to committed prediction. MLP neurons drive the final decision: N28:5086 provides the strongest single vote (+1.13 proj for L), followed by massive reinforcement from N32:3054 (+1.30 proj). L rises from 42.9% at L23 to 82.2% at L29, then 97.2% at L33. Methionine briefly competes (peaks 11.9% at L28) but lacks sufficient support. The L26 velocity event (+3.79 delta) marks the decisive commitment.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-24, AA-specific prediction features first appear: F24:5827 (23.6 proj) is a leucine-enriched channel that shifts the representation from 'hydrophobic context' to 'leucine prediction.' The L24 MLP contributes +0.43 net proj despite mixed signals, while attention begins suppressing alternatives (V drops from 20.1% to 16.3%). By L25, the model has committed to leucine as the only viable candidate.

candidates.narrative: Leucine emerges as a serious contender at L13 (18.7%) when structural contacts are integrated, competes closely with valine through L23 (42.9%), then dominates decision phase. Key support comes from F24:5827 (23.6 proj, leucine-specific attention feature), F30:2678 (35.3 proj attention feature), and decisive MLP votes: N28:5086 (+1.13 for L), N32:3054 (+1.30 for L). The L26 attention event (+2.29 delta) and L32 MLP surge (+5.70 total proj) drive L from 60% to 97% in the final layers.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L13, competitive L17-23, decisive L26-33
key_evidence: F24:5827 (attn, 23.6 proj) — leucine-specific prediction channel activates at decision boundary
N28:5086 (MLP, +1.13 proj) — strongest single leucine vote, also supports M (+0.68)
N32:3054 (MLP, +1.30 proj) — final-layer leucine specialist, also votes H (+1.17)
F33:1406 (MLP, 128.3 proj) — massive final-layer leucine feature

candidates.narrative: Valine dominates the perception phase, peaking at 29.5% at L21 as the logit lens reflects the model's assembly of a small-hydrophobic representation. This is NOT a prediction—V's prominence reflects that the structural context (buried, aliphatic) is consistent with valine-like chemistry. V competes with L through L23 (20.1%) but collapses in decision phase as leucine-specific features activate. By L29, V has dropped to 4.5%, and final probability is 0.12%.
key_evidence: L21 peak reflects small-hydrophobic representation character, not prediction
No valine-specific prediction channels activate in L24-33
Suppressed by leucine-specific MLP neurons (N28:5086, N32:3054 vote strongly for L over V)

candidates.narrative: Methionine emerges late (L17: 6.9%) as a hydrophobic alternative, peaks at L28 (11.9%) when N28:5086 votes for both L (+1.13) and M (+0.68). However, M lacks dedicated prediction channels—it benefits from leucine-supporting neurons that also weakly support methionine due to shared hydrophobic character. Final suppression comes from L32 attention (head 32:4 erases -1.60 proj) and lack of M-specific MLP support. Final probability 2.52%.
candidates.key_layers: Emerges L17, peaks L28 (11.9%), suppressed L29-33
key_evidence: N28:5086 votes M (+0.68) alongside L (+1.13) — shared hydrophobic support
Lacks dedicated prediction channels in L30-33, collapses to 2.52%

candidates.narrative: Glutamate leads the logit lens at L5-7 (peaks 26.9% at L6) as the model sequentially reads nearby charged residues in the local context (E at position 65, H at 68). This reflects the representation's encoding of local sequence chemistry, NOT a prediction. E disappears by L12 as structural contacts override local sequence signal. The early E prominence demonstrates how perception-phase logit lens outputs reflect information flow rather than model beliefs.
key_evidence: L5-7 peak reflects sequential reading of nearby E65 in local context
No structural or co-evolutionary support for charged residue at this buried position

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from encoding local sequence (charged residues S, H, E, D dominate L1-12) to encoding structural context (hydrophobic residues L, V dominate L13+). L16:12 attention head writes +1.75 proj by reading local hydrophobic positions. L17 velocity event (+4.70 delta, attention-driven) marks the integration of structural contacts. The logit lens shifts from charged-leaning to hydrophobic-leaning, with L rising from 3.9% to 14.9% and V rising to 15.7%.

Perception becomes decision. F24:5827 (23.6 proj) is the first leucine-specific prediction channel, marking the transition from 'hydrophobic context' to 'leucine prediction.' L24-25 MLPs contribute mixed signals (+0.43 and +1.55 net proj) as the model commits. L26 attention event (+3.79 delta, driven by +2.29 attn) decisively favors leucine over valine. L rises from 42.9% to 60.1%, while V drops from 20.1% to 10.8%.

Final commitment phase. N28:5086 provides the strongest single leucine vote (+1.13 proj), pushing L from 60% to 73%. L32 MLP delivers massive reinforcement (+5.70 total proj): N32:3054 (+1.30), N32:4433 (+1.10), N32:4174 (+0.90) all vote leucine. L32 attention head 32:4 suppresses alternatives (-1.60 proj). L rises from 82% to 97% in the final two layers, with F33:1406 (128.3 proj) providing final-layer leucine encoding.

deep_dives.label: Early logit lens instability (L1-12)
deep_dives.caption: Watch how the logit lens cycles through S, H, E, D, R as the model reads local sequence. These are NOT predictions—they reflect sequential encoding of nearby charged residues. F1:5480, F1:9146 encode positional context. F9:5728, F9:1281 encode secondary structure. The representation is assembling information, not making guesses.

deep_dives.label: Structural contact integration (L13-17)
deep_dives.caption: L16:12 reads local hydrophobic positions (+1.75 proj). L17 attention (+3.35 delta) integrates 8 structural contacts. The representation shifts from charged-leaning to hydrophobic-leaning as buried context dominates. This is where the model 'realizes' this is a hydrophobic core position.

deep_dives.label: Late perception features (L18)
deep_dives.caption: F18:7701 and F18:9820 (13.0 proj each) encode buried hydrophobic character. These are context-encoding features, not prediction channels. The representation is now 'about a buried aliphatic position' but not yet 'for leucine specifically.'

deep_dives.label: Decision boundary (L24)
deep_dives.caption: F24:5827 (23.6 proj) is the first leucine-specific prediction channel. This marks the transition from perception to decision. The representation shifts from 'hydrophobic context' to 'leucine prediction.' Compare to L18 features—these are qualitatively different.

deep_dives.label: MLP decision neurons (L28, L32)
deep_dives.caption: N28:5086 (+1.13 for L) and N32:3054 (+1.30 for L) are the decisive votes. L32 MLP contributes +5.70 total proj, the largest single-layer push. These neurons are leucine specialists that fire when the assembled context matches leucine's requirements.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction features (L30, L33)
deep_dives.caption: F30:2678 (35.3 proj) and F33:1406 (128.3 proj) are high-confidence leucine channels. These massive projections reflect the model's certainty. Compare their magnitude to L24 features—the model has moved from tentative commitment to absolute confidence.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts leucine by assembling a buried hydrophobic core context from 8 structural contacts and local sequence. Early layers (1-17) show unstable logit-lens projections as the model reads local charged residues sequentially, but structural integration at L13-17 shifts the representation decisively toward hydrophobic character. The L/V competition through L23 reflects the model's encoding of aliphatic context. Decision phase (L24-33) activates leucine-specific prediction channels (F24:5827, F30:2678) and MLP neurons (N28:5086, N32:3054) that recognize leucine as the optimal fit for this buried position. The 97.2% confidence reflects strong agreement between structural context and leucine's chemical properties.
